---
import Layout from '../layouts/Layout.astro';
import Hero from '../components/Hero.astro';
import Section from '../components/Section.astro';
import LoopTurn from '../components/LoopTurn.astro';
import PromptStack from '../components/PromptStack.astro';
import TurnDelta from '../components/TurnDelta.astro';
import SummaryEvolution from '../components/SummaryEvolution.astro';
import architecture from '../diagrams/architecture.svg?raw';
---
<Layout title="Leonard — a Flutter agent">
  <Hero
    name="Leonard"
    tagline="An agent that drives a real Flutter app — and knows when it's done reacting."
    pitch="Leonard is an agent harness for running Flutter apps in debug mode. It taps, types, scrolls, and looks — but it always waits for the frame to settle and lets the app's own libraries report what's going on. One trustworthy observation per turn."
  />
  <Section id="problem" title="The bet: wire an LLM straight into a running app">
    <p>Can you connect an LLM directly to a live Flutter app — over the Dart VM service — and have it perceive the app&rsquo;s real state and drive itself through it, turn after turn? That&rsquo;s the question Leonard set out to answer. The hard part is perception: a UI agent is only as good as its observation, and the classic failure is acting <em>too early</em> — reading the screen mid-animation, mid-navigation, or mid-load, then acting on a snapshot that&rsquo;s already stale.</p>
  </Section>
  <Section id="the-bet" title="Flutter gives you ground truth">
    <ul>
      <li><strong>Frame lifecycle.</strong> Flutter's scheduler knows when work is pending and when a frame committed — so &ldquo;is the app still settling?&rdquo; has a real answer.</li>
      <li><strong>Semantics tree.</strong> The screen-reader view gives interactable elements at a clean level, not raw pixels.</li>
      <li><strong>VM-service hook.</strong> A debug-mode app exposes a service the harness drives over the wire — observe, then act.</li>
    </ul>
    <p>Put together: <em>one trustworthy observation per turn.</em></p>
  </Section>
  <Section id="how-it-works" title="Architecture: a tiny policy-free host + extensions">
    <p>The host is literally a custom <code>WidgetsBinding</code> — it claims the framework's lifecycle slot in <code>main()</code>, registers a handful of VM-service extensions, and otherwise gets out of the way. Outside debug mode it doesn't install at all. Extensions live <em>in your app</em> and contribute tools, observation fragments, and lifecycle hooks.</p>
    <figure set:html={architecture} aria-label="Leonard architecture: CLI/DevTools frontends, the harness loop, model providers, and the target app with its binding + extensions."></figure>
    <p>Every turn is the same shape — the perception-action loop:</p>
    <LoopTurn />
  </Section>
  <Section id="context" title="What goes into each turn — the agent's memory">
    <p>Step 5 above said &ldquo;build the prompt.&rdquo; Here&rsquo;s what that prompt is made of — and what survives from one turn to the next.</p>
    <p>The prompt is a fixed stack of regions, sorted by how often they change:</p>
    <PromptStack />
    <p>Turn over turn, only one region is rewritten — the rest are immutable, a sliding window, or thrown away and rebuilt:</p>
    <TurnDelta />
    <p>And here&rsquo;s what that one rewritten region might look like across a session (illustrative):</p>
    <SummaryEvolution />
  </Section>
  <Section id="surfaces" title="Two surfaces, one loop">
    <ul>
      <li><strong>Scriptable CLI</strong> — <code>leonard_cli</code>: headless, for CI and batch trajectory collection.</li>
      <li><strong>In-IDE DevTools panel</strong> — a Leonard tab with <strong>Prompt</strong>, <strong>Thinking</strong>, and <strong>Timeline</strong> views; runs the same loop in-panel and shows the model's reasoning live.</li>
    </ul>
    <p>Neither reimplements anything — the loop is a library.</p>
  </Section>
  <Section id="extensions" title="Reference extensions — and write your own">
    <ul>
      <li><code>leonard_router</code> — exposes the current route stack.</li>
      <li><code>leonard_riverpod</code> — reports which providers are loading.</li>
      <li><code>leonard_dio</code> — reports in-flight HTTP requests.</li>
    </ul>
    <p>Know about <em>your</em> stack? <a href="https://github.com/memento-engineering/lenny/blob/main/docs/extension_authoring_guide.md">Write an extension</a> — it ships in your app's <code>pubspec.yaml</code>, not in the harness.</p>
  </Section>
  <Section id="models" title="Model backends">
    <ul>
      <li><code>qwen-mlx</code> — a local Qwen MoE served by swift-infer (default).</li>
      <li><code>claude</code> — Anthropic.</li>
      <li><code>openai</code> — OpenAI.</li>
    </ul>
  </Section>
  <Section id="status" title="Status: v1 PoC">
    <p>This is a proof of concept. The architecture is real and the loop runs end to end, but APIs will move, coverage is partial, and you should expect rough edges. Read the <a href="https://github.com/memento-engineering/lenny/blob/main/docs/leonard_prd_v0.5.md">PRD</a> for where it's headed.</p>
  </Section>
</Layout>
